[normal]INTRODUCTION[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]WWF is a leading global conservation organisation, employing over 5,000 staff in more than 100 countries and with more than 5 million supporte
[normal]rs across the world.  The UK charity
[normal] - WWF-U
[normal]K - was launched in 1961.  
[normal]We work in partnership with local communities, civil society organisations, governments, multinational agencies and the private sector on the issues of fresh water, biodiversity, climate change, forests, 
[normal]the 
[normal]marine
[normal] environment
[normal], sustainable consumption, 
[normal]infrastructure and energy
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We welcome the 
[normal]Environment, Food &amp; Rural Affairs 
[normal]Committee
[normal]’s Inquiry into food security
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]Our responses 
[normal]to the issues raised by the Committee 
[normal]focus on those areas 
[normal]most 
[normal]relevant to our work.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]RESPONSE[bold]S[bold] TO [bold]ISSUES RAISED BY THE COMMITTEE[bold]How best to improve UK (and EU) food security, including using resources more efficiently[bold]The relationship between the price of food and the cost of producing it[bold]The implications of volatility in global food supply and demand for UK food security[bold]The potential value and contribution of science and GM technology to UK food security[bold]How food and farming supply chains, and the current systems for traceability, can contribute to increased resilience[bold]Whether climate change risks are adequately incorporated in UK food security strategies and planning [bold]The obstacles facing food producers, including small farmers, seeking to increase production and access new markets[bold]Water security
[normal]Ecosystem degradation and biodiversity loss
[normal]Ways of increasing self[bold]-[bold]sufficiency in products for which the UK has a comparative advantage[bold]Conclusion [bold]&#xa0;
